# How is the US attempting to limit Putin's potential to profit from the oil market?

## Summary
The U.S. and its allies are taking drastic measures to limit Russia's potential to profit from the oil market. They have imposed a $60 price cap on the oil Russia continues to sell to other parts of the world <font color=#FF3399>[2,4]</font>, and have banned all seaborne imports of Russian oil as well <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. These moves are intended to limit Russia's ability to fund its war in Ukraine <font color=#FF3399>[2]</font> and have been met with skepticism from analysts and officials <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>. However, the U.S. and its allies remain determined to reduce Russia's oil revenues, as the price cap and embargo come into effect on December 5 <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>.

## Claims
| Claim Sentence | Context |
|---|---|
|<font color=#FF3399>[1]</font> A price cap on Russian crude oil in response to the countrys invasion and ongoing war in Ukraine will go into effect on December 5.<a href="https://www.energypolicy.columbia.edu/publications/what-success-or-failure-would-look-price-cap-russian-oil/" target="_blank">Source</a>| A price cap on Russian crude oil in response to the countrys invasion and ongoing war in Ukraine will go into effect on December 5. The price cap is an effort to reduce Russias oil revenues while maintaining adequate supplies of crude on the global energy market.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[2]</font> The U.S. has joined the European Union, the Group of Seven nations, and Australia to cap the price of Russian oil at $60 a barrel.<a href="https://finance.yahoo.com/news/us-joins-eu-and-g-7-to-cap-russian-oil-prices-at-60-barrel-232259347.html" target="_blank">Source</a>| The U.S. has joined the European Union, the Group of Seven nations, and Australia to cap the price of Russian oil at $60 a barrel. The U.S. has been in detailed talks with allies for months about setting a price cap on Russian oil to reduce the country's revenue as it continues its invasion in Ukraine.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[3]</font> Also, the U.S., other members of the Group of Seven leading economies, the EU and Australia are imposing a $60 price cap on the oil Russia continues to sell to other parts of the world.<a href="https://www.npr.org/2022/12/02/1139477837/russia-oil-revenue-sanctions-price-cap-g7-eu-import-ban" target="_blank">Source</a>| The United States and its allies have delivered a double blow to Russia aimed at starving its oil revenues. First, the European Union is banning all seaborne imports of Russian oil, a move that takes effect Monday. Also, the U.S., other members of the Group of Seven leading economies, the EU and Australia are imposing a $60 price cap on the oil Russia continues to sell to other parts of the world. The two moves are intended to limit Russia's ability to fund its war in Ukraine but are designed to prevent disruptions in oil supplies that could cause higher prices.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[4]</font> On December 3, 2022, G7 members formally set the highly anticipated price cap on Russian oil at 60 USD per barrel.<a href="https://sanctionsnews.bakermckenzie.com/g7-sets-price-cap-for-russian-oil-at-usd-60-per-barrel/" target="_blank">Source</a>| On December 3, 2022, G7 members formally set the highly anticipated price cap on Russian oil at 60 USD per barrel. This price cap applies to crude oil, petroleum oils, and oils obtained from bituminous minerals which originate in or are exported from Russia.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[5]</font> The $60 per barrel price ceiling and embargo are aimed at hurting Moscow's fuel revenues but some analysts and officials are skeptical the efforts will work.<a href="https://www.npr.org/2022/12/05/1139880140/russia-ukraine-war-oil-cap-russian-strikes-putin-biden-dec-5" target="_blank">Source</a>| And the two leaders remarked to reporters about the idea of speaking to Russian President Vladimir Putin. Western countries reached a deal for a price cap on Russian oil, and the EU is banning most Russian oil imports. The $60 per barrel price ceiling and embargo are aimed at hurting Moscow's fuel revenues but some analysts and officials are skeptical the efforts will work. The Kremlin said "nyet" to the idea of talks with President Biden, after the U.S. leader remarked he'd be willing to have contact with Russian President Vladimir Putin.|
